  "estimatedMinutes": 40,
  "concept": "This lesson covers the single most useful thing you will do in French: introducing yourself and asking who someone is. Three pieces of grammar make it work.\n\nFirst, the verb être (\"to be\") — the backbone of self-description. Learn it cold; you will use it constantly:\n  je suis (I am), tu es (you are, informal), il/elle est (he/she is),\n  nous sommes (we are), vous êtes (you are, formal/plural), ils/elles sont (they are).\nWith jobs and nationalities you use être and NO article: je suis professeur (not \"je suis un professeur\"), je suis indienne.\n\nSecond, nationalities agree with gender. The masculine is the base form; the feminine usually adds -e, which often makes a final consonant come alive in pronunciation: français → française (the masculine -s is silent, but you hear the -se as a \"z\"). Some double the consonant: indien → indienne, italien → italienne, canadien → canadienne. As adjectives (\"I am French\"), they stay lowercase: je suis français.\n\nThird, tu vs vous. Use tu with friends, family, and people your own age; use vous with strangers, elders, teachers, and any group of people. The choice changes the verb (tu es vs vous êtes) and the question \"what is your name?\": comment tu t'appelles ? (informal) or comment vous appelez-vous ? (formal).\n\nPut together, a simple introduction is: \"Bonjour, je m'appelle… Je suis [nationality]. Je suis [job].\" To ask back: \"Et vous ? Quelle est votre nationalité ?\"\n\nDon't aim for perfect — aim to say three correct sentences about yourself out loud.",
